	<div class="editorial">
	<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" align="right"><tr><td><span id="iAd">
</span></td></tr></table>
<span class=dateline>December  18, 2003</span> - In one of his final days as the Community Manager for EverQuest, Alan VanCouvering, now a Game Designer, sat down to answer ten questions about the upcoming changes to melee classes.<BR>
<BR></div></div><div id="intelliTxt"><div class="editorial">
Feel free to <A HREF="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?topic=61341962&replies=0">discuss this article</A> on our <A HREF="http://vnboards.ign.com/board.asp?brd=5001">EQ General Board</A>.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
<CENTER><B>EverQuest Melee Changes Q&A</B><BR>
<I>Answered by Alan VanCouvering, Game Designer - EverQuest </I></CENTER><BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> For those who know nothing about what you've planned, can you outline your basic goals with the redesign of melee in EQ and the timetable over which this will occur? <BR>
<BR>
<B>Alan VanCouvering:</B> The goal of the melee enhancement is to repair some balance issues between the melee classes and hybrid classes and to make playing a melee character more fun.  To do this we are adding a set of skills that only melee characters can use.  These skills can be used when an opponent makes a mistake or when the character makes an exceptional maneuver.<BR>
<BR>
At the same time we are changing the way that disciplines work for all characters.  The new skills and all disciplines will require an expenditure of endurance (a new calculated statistic).  Moving disciplines to the new system allows us much more flexibility with them, and makes adjusting them much easier.<BR>
<BR>
The enhancements are already on Test.  We plan to move the changes to disciplines to the Live servers on December 18th.  The melee skills will need more testing, and won't be moving to the Live servers until some time in January.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> EverQuest is still the most popular North American MMORPG. Are you at all worried that despite the demand from the community, you could alienate many users with sweeping changes to such a core element as melee? <BR>
<BR>
<B>Alan VanCouvering:</B> That's always a concern.  However, I think you would find that our players would say that leaving it as is was would have been a bigger risk.  :)<BR>
<BR>
We always have to evaluate the potential risk of alienating folks.  In this case we are not changing the way melee works at the core, we are adding an enhancement on top of that system with the hope that it will make playing a melee character more fun and address some of the concerns folks have.  This certainly could be too much of a change for some players.  But we feel that it makes EverQuest a much better game, so we have to take that risk.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> The "opening system" has people's interest piqued, but how do you intend to ensure that it is fun and not just micromanagement? <BR>
<BR>
<B>Alan VanCouvering:</B> Testing and feedback.  Initial impressions from the Test server indicate that we have more tweaking to do to it than we had anticipated.  So we're going to leave it there and get more feedback so we can make changes until we have it were we want it.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> While these things may make combat more fun, fun does not always translate to balance. Will you be increasing the overall power of warrior-classes in general so that they are more competitive? If so, are you worried about creating dramatically shorter fights? <BR>
<BR>
<B>Alan VanCouvering:</B> We worry about all of that.  There have been concerns from some folks that we'd over-balance things.  There is certainly a problem that needs to be addressed, we can't be afraid to fix it because of the possibility of alienating folks or of missing the mark when it comes to balance.  We'll work on it until it's right on Test.  I have no doubt that we'll get very close to the goal with the melee enhancement.<BR>
	</div>
</div>
<!-- // 3 closing </DIV> are in full_ign_ratings_box.jsp  --Frank -->
